        "title": "How to properly name an enum to use in switch case in Java Programming?",
        "body": "<p>On my example I'm using a <code>state<\/code> and <code>action<\/code> in <code>switch case<\/code> statement. I'm a little bit confuse whether to use a single <code>enum<\/code> which has state and action.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Example:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<pre><code>switch(gun.state) {\n     case RELOAD: gun.state = RELOADING break;\n     case RELOADING: break;\n     case FIRE: gun.state = FIRING break;\n     case FIRING:  break;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p><strong>Question<\/strong> should I create a single <code>enum<\/code> or categorize it by action and state?<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>switch(gun.action) {}\nswitch(gun.state) {}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p><strong>Suggestions/Answer<\/strong>\nBased on the answer of Erwin Bolwidt, should I create another <code>enum<\/code> and categorize it by action and state?<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public enum Action {FIRE, RELOAD};\npublic enum State {FIRING, RELOADING}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
